1.1) What do you notice about missing data? How would you plan to handle variables with missing values? Will you handle missingness the same for all variables - explain why or why not?

There were missing values for pattern, but looking at the dictionary NA referred to the pattern being unable to categorize. I recoded NA to be no_category. There is also one missing value for number of photos and adoption fee, since these are numeric predictors I can use step_impute_median when making recipes.

1.2) What do you notice about the range of your numeric values?

Age has a minimum of -2 and a maximum of 1100. These are both impossible values as a pet can not be in the negative ages and 1100 months is about 92 years which is also impossible.

Recipe for linear model

Write a recipe to fit a linear model to predict AdoptionTime from all predictors. Informed from your EDA above, be sure to include the following steps in your recipe: - Step to address missing data - Step to collapse at least one categorical predictor - Step to normalize numeric predictors - Appropriate steps for categorical predictors - Include the interaction between ExpectedSize and Age (regardless of what your EDA above revealed)

rec_1 <- 
  recipe(adoption_time ~ ., data = data_1_train) |>
  step_impute_median(number_photos, adoption_fee, age) |>
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) |>
  step_other(pattern, threshold = 10, other = "other") |>
  step_interact(terms = ~ expected_size:age) |>
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors())

1.6) For each step that you added to your recipe above, write one sentence explaining why you added each step.

I first imputed the mean for number_photos and adoption_fee because they each had one missing value and are numeric. Then I normalized the numeric predictors so they are all on the same scale. Next I collapsed pattern observations that were less than 10 into an âotherâ category. Then I dummy coded the nominal predictors so the models can run. Lastly, I added the interaction between expected size and age.

2.1) Which classifier (statistical algorithm) would you select and why?

Based on the performance metrics of both the logisitic regression and QDA, I would select QDA. I would select this one because the overall accuracy in all bootstrapped samples was higher (0.95 vs 0.92 in logistic).

2.2) What does your best classifier being a logistic regression vs QDA suggest about the structure of your data?

My best classifier being a QDA might suggest that the data was not linear since QDA can handle non-linearity. Because QDA outperformed logistic regression, it might suggest that the decision boundary was not linear and needed a more flexible model.

2.3) Why use bootstrapped resampling to make this decision?

Bootstrapping resampling allows for a reliable estimate of well each model performs on average. It does this by averaging the performance metric across multiple samples obtained by bootstrapping resampling. In this case, we were more concerned about a precise selection metric rather than worrying about bias and bootstrapping is best for this scenario.

Split your data into training and test sets. Hold out 25% of the data as the test set. Only use the test set to evaluate your final model. Make sure this split is reproducible

splits_test3 <- data_3 |> 
  initial_split(prop = 0.75)

data_trn3 <- splits_test3 |> 
  analysis()

data_test3 <- splits_test3 |> 
  assessment()

Create 100 bootstrap splits with the training data, stratified on y. Make it reproducible

splits_boot3 <- data_3 |> 
  bootstraps(times = 100, strata = "y")

Create a simple recipe to predict y from all provided predictors. Create features from the numeric predictors in their raw, untransformed state

rec_3 <- recipe(y~., data = data_trn3)
rec_prep_3 <- rec_3 |> 
  prep(training = data_trn3)
feat_trn_3 <- rec_prep_3 |> 
  bake(new_data = data_trn3)
feat_test_3 <- rec_prep_3 |> 
  bake(data_test3)

Hyperparameter grid

Set up a hyperparameter grid to tune both the mixture hyperparameter (alpha) and the penalty hyperparameter (lambda)

grid_glmnet <- expand_grid(penalty = exp(seq(-4, 2, length.out = 5)),
                           mixture = seq(0, 1, length.out = 11))

Tune model

Tune your glmnet model using the above recipe and your bootstrap splits. Use RMSE as your performance metric

fits_glmnet <- xfun::cache_rds(
  expr = {
    linear_reg(penalty = tune(), 
               mixture = tune()) |> 
    set_engine("glmnet") |> 
    tune_grid(preprocessor = rec_3, 
              resamples = splits_boot3, 
              grid = grid_glmnet, 
              metrics = metric_set(rmse))
  
  },
  rerun = rerun_setting,
  dir = "cache/007/",
  file = "fits_glmnet")

Do anything else you need to determine that you have found the best model configuration among possible hyperparameters

plot_hyperparameters(fits_glmnet, hp1 = "penalty", hp2= "mixture", metric = "rmse")

3.1) Is your best model more of a ridge or lasso regression? How can you tell?

Since a penalty of 0 is true ridge regression and a penalty of 1 is true LASSO regression, I would say mine is more of a ridge regression. This is because I got a best penalty of 0.1 which is closer to 0.

Assess the performance of your model in test

Print the performance of your best model in test and make a plot to visualize the relationship between raw and predicted y in your test set.

# Fit best Model
fit_glmnet <- linear_reg(penalty = select_best(fits_glmnet)$penalty,
                         mixture = select_best(fits_glmnet)$mixture) |> 
  set_engine("glmnet") |> 
  fit(y ~ ., data = feat_trn_3)

# Visualize
predictions <- predict(fit_glmnet, new_data = feat_trn_3)
plot_truth(truth = feat_trn_3$y, estimate = predictions$.pred)

# RMSE
glmnet_rmse_trn <- rmse_vec(truth = feat_trn_3$y,
         estimate = predict(fit_glmnet, feat_trn_3)$.pred) # 1.01
glmnet_rmse_test <- rmse_vec(truth = feat_test_3$y,
         estimate = predict(fit_glmnet, feat_test_3)$.pred) # 0.9326

3.2) Does your test RMSE seem like a good fit to you? What is the worst value you might have expected for RMSE and why?

Yes my test RMSE seems like a good fit because the test and training error are relatively similar and low. This means the model was not overfit to the training data and able to perform well in test data. The worst value I may have expected for RMSE would be something drastically higher than 1.01 (training set RMSE).

3.3) Explain why you see a difference between your best modelâs RMSE in training vs test. Give one example of something that could INCREASE this difference

The model is going to perform differently with each new set of data, so no two sets will have the exact same RMSE. However, if the training set RMSE is a lot lower than the test setâs, it could be the result of overfitting. Some things that could increase overfitting in the training set (and thus increase the difference in RMSE) would be a small training sample or a complex model.
